<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Overseas registration</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the Nursing and Midwifery Council</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (NMC </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">00</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">0</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Nursing and Midwifery Council is an independent statutory regulator that exists to protect the public.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Nurses and midwives must be registered with the NMC to practise in the UK. We set standards of education and practice for nursing and midwifery, and we maintain a register of those qualified to practise and in good professional standing. We act when questions are raised about our registrants’ fitness to practise, and we can impose sanctions including striking off where necessary to protect the public.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In 2012 the Professional Standards Authority (PSA) conducted a strategic review of the NMC. It concluded that the NMC was protecting the public, but that it needed to make significant improvements in its regulatory practice and business management in order to be deemed an effective and efficient regulator. The PSA set us a challenging set of performance targets to be met in the main over two years.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The PSA also publishes an annual performance report on each regulator, and the most recent was published in June 2013. This report covers the first months of a two year improvement programme, and although the PSA judged that we had not yet met eight of its standards for good regulation, the tenor of the report is positive and it recognises that the NMC is making progress.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Meanwhile expectations of regulators are moving on significantly. After the report of the Francis Inquiry into failings at Mid Staffordshire Foundation Trust there is an expectation that healthcare organisations including regulators will do more to keep patients safe, by using their data to anticipate risk, and by demonstrating greater proactivity in responding when warning signs emerge. There is also an imperative for system and professional regulators to work better together to detect and respond to risk. As a consequence the NMC is pursuing improvements in its core functions and preparing to meet new expectations of regulators. These include the introduction of revalidation for nurses and midwives, a move encouraged by the Health Committee.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Responding to Francis</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Francis Report has been highly significant for the NMC.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We published our full response in July 2013 which included a series of actions with timescales. The commitments we made include:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">To evaluate our education standards and review our code to ensure that Francis themes such as candour and compassion are appropriately covered.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">To raise our profile as recommended by the Francis report so that patients, the public and employers understand our role and get the support they need if they have concerns about a nurse or midwife.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">To implement the changes to our fitness to practise legislation announced by the Prime Minister in response to the Francis report and thereby deliver improvements to the timeliness and quality of our casework.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">To strengthen our collaborative work with other regulators – we have revised our memorandum of understanding with the CQC and will have new protocols for information sharing and joint work by the end of 2013. We want to extend this work to other UK regulators in 2014.</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We are continuing to hear cases arising from events at Mid Staffordshire and the Committee will understand that there are limits to how much we can say about these in a public document or session.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Code</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Robert Francis was positive about the clarity of our code and education standards in conveying to nurses and midwives the over-riding duty of care for patients and service users. We will review our code in 2014 in preparation for the introduction of revalidation and in doing so will consider what else </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">we can do to strengthen messages, including those around compassion, candour and raising concerns.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We have taken account of the Health Committee’s post-legislative scrutiny of the Mental Health Act 2007, the report of which was published in July 2013. We will ensure our code review takes account of the Committee’s views, and they accord with our own sense that the revised code could usefully say more about professionals’ advocacy on behalf of patients. Our education standards are clearer on this point.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Education</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The first nurses to graduate under our new standards will be taking up their first posts in Autumn 201</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">4</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> so it is too early for a full review of our education standards, but we have committed to starting evaluation of the ‘front end’ of the process from 2014, as values-based recruitment has been of concern. There has been one review of nurse education since the introduction of the 2010 standards, the Willis Review, which was positive about our new standards.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In its response to Francis the government went further than the Inquiry in suggesting up to a year’s experience as a healthcare assistant might be a pre-requisite for entering nursing degrees. We are participating in Health Education England’s steering group to pilot some variations on this theme.</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Evaluation of the HEE pilots will provide evidence about whether mandatory HCA experience is an effective and cost effective way of ensuring those entering nursing have the requisite values.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We already enable universities to give credit for relevant pre-degree experience and we require all nursing and midwifery students to spend 50 per cent of their training in healthcare settings, working with supervision alongside experienced professionals. Nursing degrees are structured so that students must be signed off by higher education and practice-based staff for progression between years of study, so that they have to be performing well and commanding confidence in the theory and the practice of nursing. In practice many of those embarking on nursing programmes do have prior caring experience already.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Fitness to practise</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We have made good progress in this important area of our work over the last year. The NMC received 4,106 referrals/complaints in 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">13. This represents an average of 16 referrals every day, or 80 in a working week.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Each case must be looked at carefully and initial decisions such as whether to recommend an interim order imposition must be taken with speed and accuracy. We have a key performance indicator (KPI) of 80 per cent of interim order decisions taken within 28 days of receipt of a referral. In 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">13 our average performance was 64 per cent; we are now performing comfortably above the KPI – the July 2013 figure was 91 per cent. Four weeks is the best average performance among the healthcare regulators.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We have made strong improvements in the length of the investigation stage of the process. In 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">13 68 per cent of investigations were completed in under 12 months; the July 2013 figure is 88 per cent against a 90 per cent target. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Our most challenging target relates to bringing cases that have been investigated to hearing, or adjudication. Our target is to achieve 90 per cent of adjudications in six months or less by December 2014. This KPI is linked to the £20M grant we received from the DH.</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">13, 39 per cent of cases were adjudicated in less than six months. Figures for July 2013 were 30 per cent.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In August 2013 we achieved 47 per cent. The number is low at the moment because a high proportion of the cases going through the adjudication stage are from the backlog, and are old and complex.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Committee has also been concerned that our oldest cases are completed. Our internal target is to ensure all historical cases are scheduled by the end of September 2013. This is on track at the time of writing, save for those cases (c.40) that cannot be progressed for reasons beyond the NMC’s control, such as ongoing police investigation or ill health on the part of key participants. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In 2012, the Committee welcomed the fact that the NMC had clear KPIs for fitness to practise but urged us to make them more ambitious. Our current KPIs separate the investigation and adjudication stages, and as the Committee has pointed out the public interest is in the time taken from the point of referral to resolution. Assuming we meet our current adjudication stage KPI by the end of 2014, we envisage recommending to Council a more ambitious KPI in the order of 90 per cent of all cases resolved in or under 15 months for 2015</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">16. This would bring our performance in line with other regulators.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We are clear that the current level of fitness to practise expenditure is not sustainable. We urgently need changes to our legislation which ties us to an inefficient regulatory model. The Prime Minister announced two changes to our legislation in the wake of the Francis Report, enabling us to employ case examiners from July 2014 to direct investigations and make early stage decisions, and giving us the power to review our own cases. We hope the Law Commission review of healthcare regulatory legislation will go further, particularly in giving us the ability to dispose of cases early by requiring undertakings on the part of the registrant. The General Medical Council already has this power and disposes of 65 per cent of cases at the initial assessment stage, whereas we dispose of 40 per cent.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We have made many other improvements in fitness to practise since we were last before the Committee. Senior lawyers now undertake a criterion-based review of hearing outcomes and refer concerns to a decision review group. We have introduced voluntary removal and consensual panel determinations for specific cases where the registrant admits fault and impairment. We have focussed on improving the witness experience and we are now receiving better feedback from participants in fitness to practise hearings. We are planning for the introduction of case examiners in July 2014 and scoping options for a regional field force to contribute to fitness to practise liaison, promoting revalidation and contributing to preventative activity such as risk summits and quality surveillance groups in England. FtP will remain the focus of our attention for the foreseeable future.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Revalidation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We have acted on the Committee’s recommendation that we make swift progress towards introducing revalidation for nurses and midwives. We attracted considerable media and professional interest in our September 2013 Council decision on revalidation and positive press coverage has enabled us to promote the value that revalidation can add to public protection. The options under consideration were developed with extensive stakeholder engagement and the preferred option involves self confirmation of continuing fitness to practise at the point of renewal, with third party input in the form of employer confirmation, and feedback from others including patients and peers. This model was deemed likely to make the best contribution to public protection within the parameters of our current legislation, and with affordability and proportionality in mind. We remain committed to implementing revalidation from the end of 2015. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We welcome the positive references to nurse and midwife revalidation in Don Berwick’s review of patient safety, and the Health Minister Dan Poulter’s statement: ‘I support the NMC in its drive to introduce revalidation – it will improve safety and quality of care and reassure patients that nurses remain fit to carry out their important work.’.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overseas registration </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Since our last appearance before the Committee we have undertaken assurance work on our overseas registration process. Intelligence from other agencies alongside concerns of our own prompted a review of applications from one non-EU country in the first instance. Based on information received we commissioned KPMG to provide an independent audit of applicants from that country and this confirmed some historical documentary weaknesses prior to 2007 and strong control measures from that date. KPMG is now conducting a further audit programme on a range of overseas populations predominantly focused on 2002</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">06 records. This exercise has identified a number of records that we are investigating further. For the first tranche of 500 records audited, further investigation (of 14 in total) allayed any concerns.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We are continuing to strengthen our overseas registrations processes. We have introduced face to face ID checks and invested in passport scanning software to reduce the risk of fraud. We are </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">currently consulting on a new competency test for overseas applicants, to be introduced in Autumn 2014.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Health Minister Dan Poulter stated that he was ‘greatly encouraged by the proactive approach being taken by the new leadership of the NMC to ensuring patient safety by strengthening and modernising their registration requirements for overseas nurses.’.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Revision of the EU recognition of professional qualifications directive</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Committee has maintained a keen interest in the impact of EU provisions that facilitate labour market mobility on regulation and hence, public protection. We welcome many of the changes that have now been proposed for the revision of Directive 2005/36/EC, having lobbied with other regulators for increased emphasis on patient safety in its new provisions. These include changes to the minimum training standards for nursing and midwifery</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">to include</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">up to date competencies and outcomes based skills requirements, an alert mechanism for the proactive sharing of fitness to practise information, and a requirement that member states should promote continuing competence through systems of continuing professional development. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We are however concerned about aspects of other proposals in the revised directive which we believe may limit the ability of regulators to protect the public. These include the introduction of partial access to a profession for some recognition cases and the inability of regulators to impose a stringent registration process for migrants seeking to move to the UK to provide temporary and occasional services. We are currently analysing the revisions to the Directive, and we will be holding discussions with the Department of Health in advance of the introduction of the changes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Testing of the English language competence of EU migrants</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">A new provision of the Directive emphasises the importance of language competency of migrants, particularly where there are implications for patient and public safety, and it does</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">indicate that language competency can be assessed before migrants provide care. It goes on to state however that testing must take place before access to the profession but </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">after </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">recognition of the migrant’s qualification. This is not helpful for the NMC due to the fact that under current legislation nurses and midwives gain access to the register immediately on recognition of their qualification, and are thus able to work as a nurse or midwife straight away. This process is different to that proposed for the General Medical Council for example, where assessment of language competence will be linked to a license to practise, as opposed to the separate initial recognition and registration process. The NMC will liaise closely with the Department of Health as the revised Directive is transposed in order to address this issue.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Registration fee</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">One of our most important means of protecting the public is acting to limit or prevent the practice of nurses and midwives who do not meet our standards. Fitness to practise is the most costly aspect of our operations; in 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">13 77, per cent of our expenditure was on fitness to practise</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In the wake of the Francis report there is a heightened awareness of risks to patient safety and this is contributing to an increase in referrals.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">2013</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">14 figures to date suggest a 17 per cent increase on 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">13 averages.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We work with employers to ensure they understand which cases should be referred to us, and the Committee may recall that we have brought the greater part of our investigations in house to ensure that the right cases – those likely to result in a sanction – go forward to hearing. We are doing what we can to identify and implement efficiencies but there is a limit to what we can achieve within our current legislation.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In 2012 the Health Committee advised against an increase in the NMC’s registration fee. This was given due weight in March 2013 when Council most recently reviewed the fee and no increase was made for 2014</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">15. We have introduced an annual formal review of the fee level and our strengthened financial modelling enables us to give Council robust evidence of our cost forecasts. The Committee recommended improvements to our financial modelling and fitness to practise forecasting and these have been implemented. We benefited from a £20 million grant in 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">13 which has enabled us to limit the fee rise for two years. Our financial projections are based on an annual fee of </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">£120 from March 2015. In March 2014 it is likely we will need to advise the Council to consult on a further fee rise, of a sum to be decided.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Council acted on the Committee’s 2012 recommendation to consider a phased payment scheme but it did not opt to introduce one at this stage because it deemed the administrative costs too high in a context of manual registrations. It will give consideration to phased payment when our technology would support this development without upward pressure on fee levels.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Raising our profile</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Francis Report recommended that we raise our profile with the public and other stakeholders. We have refreshed our guidance on raising concerns which was launched at our September 2013 Council by Helene Donnelly, the nurse who raised concerns at Mid Staffordshire. We have a vibrant Patient and Public Engagement Forum which plays an active role in improving our work. We have undertaken extensive four nations engagement around revalidation in 2013, and our plans have been widely and mainly positively reported in the national media. We are relaunching our dedicated helpline for directors of nursing (including independent sector) and local supervising authority midwifery officers who wish to discuss in confidence potential fitness to practise cases or other matters of public protection.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Organisational health of the NMC</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Leadership and governance</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Committee recommended a period of stability in the leadership of the NMC and we have benefited from continuity over the past 12 months. The chair has overseen the reconstitution of Council and a successful recruitment drive resulted in high calibre appointments. The new Council is offering appropriate scrutiny and challenge, and demonstrating the skills and appetite for strategic leadership. The interim post holder has been confirmed as substantive chief executive, and this appointment was widely welcomed by external stakeholders.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">A governance review has led to more streamlined and responsive decision making processes and our change board is overseeing the improvements to which we have committed in response to the Professional Standards Authority, the Health Committee and the Francis Inquiry and related reviews.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Finance and ICT</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The NMC has worked quickly to improve financial management and controls. Council approved a finance strategy in October 2012 and our financial assumptions were externally verified. Council’s financial expertise has been strengthened and finance is well scrutinised. Finance and business planning staff conduct monthly meetings with every directorate to ensure delivery against plans is on time and on budget.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We are working towards the restoration of available free reserves to the minimum target level of £10m by January 2016. Our projected year end reserves remain on target to be £7.4m by 31 March 2014. We have planned for more progress on this KPI in 2014</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">15.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We have acted on the Committee’s recommendation that we secure immediate IT improvements as well as delivering a longer term IT strategy. Council will consider a three year strategy in November 2013, and improvements completed or underway include:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">36.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Better links between the register and case management systems mitigating the risk that case outcomes are not reflected on the register</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">36.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Upgrades to outdated desktop technology </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">36.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Initial online registration facilities and technical roadmap for revalidation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">36.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">New</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">system for customer relationship management </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63.8pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">36.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Enhanced reports and dashboards for fitness to practise.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Staff culture and turnover</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Committee expressed its desire to see a significant reduction in staff turnover from our 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">13 figure of 36 per cent. A number of initiatives including a pay and grading review and a learning and organisational development strategy will contribute to improvements in retention, and Council is monitoring our performance at each meeting. Our target is a 23.2 per cent average by the end of March 2014 and the figure at August 2013 is 26.9 per cent, which is a significant improvement. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We have also conducted a comprehensive staff survey and a staff group is monitoring progress against an action plan arising from staff comments. The survey confirmed we have lots to do but it also demonstrated a high degree of understanding about the regulatory role of the NMC and strong commitment at all levels to improvement and effectiveness. Council Members, the executive Board and all staff are participating in training about NMC values and behaviours. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Concluding comments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">When we last spoke to the Committee we were clear that the changes we needed to make for the NMC to become an efficient and effective regulator would take at least two years. This is also the assessment of the Professional Standards Authority. A year on, we have solid progress to report, and we feel confident that plans are in place to deliver further improvements and to meet new challenges over the year ahead.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span></p></div></body></html>